Library

Target IP: 10.10.127.104

Scanning


There are two TCP ports open on the target machine: SSH and HTTP. I will start enumeration with the HTTP application on port 80.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

The webpage above is displayed for this application. Performing a directory search shows robots.txt exists. Browsing to this page shows the entry rockyou. And this main page contains an interesting username meliodas. Since there are no other login pages for the web application -- maybe, I can bruteforce the SSH application?

Exploitation


Bruteforcing as the user meliodas with the rockyou.txt file returns a valid credential meliodas:iloveyou1.


Now I have a foothold on the machine.

Privilege Escalation


The Python file bak.py can be executed with root privileges. This program imports a module called zipfile. I can perform library hijacking here by creating a new zipfile module with the reverse shell script inside it.


And now I have a root shell. I put the Python reverse shell script inside the malicious module. When the bak.py is executed with sudo, it will import the malicious module and give me a root shell on port 8443 on my local machine.

Flags


The user.txt flag once I gained a foothold on the machine using SSH.


The root.txt flag once I used library hijacking to gain a root shell.
